Assuming that the database already contains a table called "EMPLOYEE", here is an example of how to create a new role called "ROLE1" and grant it select and update permissions on the table:

```
USE [your_database_name];

-- Create the new role
CREATE ROLE ROLE1;

-- Grant select and update permissions on the EMPLOYEE table to the ROLE1 role
GRANT SELECT, UPDATE ON dbo.EMPLOYEE TO ROLE1;
```

In this example, replace "your_database_name" with the name of your database, and "EMPLOYEE" with the name of your table if it's different. The "dbo" before the table name represents the database schema; again, replace it with the correct schema name if it's different.

After running this code, the ROLE1 role will have select and update permissions on the EMPLOYEE table. You can then add individual users to ROLE1 to grant them the same permissions.

Here is an example of adding two users (USER1 and USER2) to the ROLE1 role, while preventing USER1 from having update authority on the EMPLOYEE table:

```
USE [your_database_name];

-- Add the two users to the ROLE1 role
EXEC sp_addrolemember 'ROLE1', 'USER1';
EXEC sp_addrolemember 'ROLE1', 'USER2';

-- Revoke the update permission on EMPLOYEE table for USER1
DENY UPDATE ON dbo.EMPLOYEE TO USER1;
```

In this example, the `sp_addrolemember` stored procedure is used to add both users (USER1 and USER2) to the ROLE1 role. 

To prevent USER1 from having update authority on the EMPLOYEE table, the `DENY` permission is used to revoke the update permission on the table for USER1.

After running this code, both USER1 and USER2 will belong to the ROLE1 role, but only USER2 will be able to update the EMPLOYEE table.
